Admiralty Park 3Feb09. Tan KH

One of the most noticeable animals here are the band of Long-tailed Macaques.
Hairy Monkey, Very loud

Its face is narrow, but long. Its eyes are close together, and in between them is a brown line leading down to its nose. Its body is covered in light brown and white fur, and its tail is about 95cm long.

The Crab-eating Macaque is a monkey that is that is primitively native to southeastern asia. It is also known as the long-tailed macaque due to its characteristically long tail. These monkey are considered sacred in some temples and are incredibly intelligent with many accounts of them using tools to obtain food.
Common Singaporean monkey. Don't know the scientific name.

This monkey is common in Singapore and can be found near forests/beaches. Its body is approximately 45cm, and its tail about 55cm (also nicknamed "long-tailed"). Its fur is a grayish-brown color on the backs, legs, and arms, but the underside of the monkey is a slightly lighter olive to beige tone. However, its skin is pure brown. The monkeys' fur is long and seems to sway in one direction. Their face is pinkish-grey with really prominent eyelids and the fur on their head swept back to form something that is similar to a crest on the midline. If you look closely, you can also see that the monkeys have relatively sharp teeth and have cheek whiskers. The hands of the monkey is very similar to that of humans (5 fingers, proportionate sized arms/fingers). As seen in the picture, the monkeys traveled in a group and followed a leader, as well as hang around large groups in general.

Monkey with reddish brown hair on its back, and grey hair on its belly. It was crawling over the sidewalk and going towards the forest. It was about 30 cm tall when it was crawling. It was about 40cm long excluding the length of the tail. It did not react even when we had an eye contact

Had dark grey colored tail, Some parts of head and back was brown, some parts were grey. Hands were dark grey. Face color was grey. Seemed moving in small groups? Body size(excluding tail) was about 60cm? Tail length seemed slightly shorter than body.
A group of monkeys found at MacRitchie Reservoir Park. They have brown hair. There are many young monkeys as well as older monkeys.

Common in most of Singapore's forested areas, this specimen was caught escaping my camera when this photograph was taken. They appear to be fairly common in the area, given that many signs warning visitors not to feed or agitate these monkeys have been found.

This playful monkey was considered a rare sight in the area, since I have never seen one specimen in the area after working in the Live Turtle and Tortoise Museum in the Chinese Gardens itself. Here, the cheeky monkey had overturned a trash bin to get at the food inside. It did not flee when I approached it to get a better shot; some of the wild monkeys in more forested areas of Singapore also seem to have developed this scavenger and aggressive personality. For example, in the Central Catchment Area, visitors are warned to keep plastic bags out of sight, lest monkeys attack the visitors in the hope to robbing the unwary of food. It seems like the worrying trend and nasty habit of seeking food from anthropogenic sources is catching on, as these photos show.

1. Scientific & Common Name(s)¬†
The distinctive long-tail of this primate identifies it as a long-tailed macaque. Colloquially it is also sometimes referred to as the crab-eating macaque. Scientifically, it is known as Macaca fascicularis.

2. Habitat & Geographic Range¬†
The long-tailed macaque covers a huge range of habitats and geographic area, making it one of the most versatile and resilient primate species. Naturally, long-tailed macaques are found in a number of forest environments such as primary and secondary forest, mangroves, swamps, and riverine and coastal forests. Macaques also adapt well to habitats that have been disturbed by human activity such as plantation areas (Sha et al., 2009). This particular specimen in the Bukit Timah area of Singapore. These primates are native to Singapore (although the rapid urban development over the past few decades has lead to a decline in their numbers) but can also be found throughout the southern parts of Southeast Asia (e.g. Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand, Laos, Vietnam, Myanmar, Bangladesh), and Sundaland (e.g. Borneo, Sumatra, Java) (Liedigk et al., 2015). Due to human activity, the long-tailed macaque has also been introduced into areas outside of their natural range such as Mauritius, Hong Kong, and West Papua (Sha et al., 2009).

3. Size /Weight & Lifespan
The tail of the long-tailed macaque, its characteristic feature, is, on average, between 40cm-65cm in length. Long-tailed macaques display sexual dimorphism in size and weight between males and females. Males are between 40cm and 65cm in length on average, and weigh between 5kg to 8kg. Females on the other hand tend to be between 38cm and 50cm in length, and weigh between 2.5kg to 6kg (Lang, 2006). The average lifespan is about 15-30 years, but closer to 30 years in captivity (AnAge, n.d.). ‚Ä®

4. Diet
The majority of a long-tailed macaques diet consists of fruit, flowers, nuts, seeds, insects, and tubers. That being said, as we have seen before, these primates are very versatile and will become more omnivorous if available food resources change. They will also steal food from humans in more urbanized areas, which is one of the major sources of human-macaque conflict in Singapore (Hadi et al., 2007, Malaivijitnond et al., 2007).

5. Reproduction & Communication
Reproduction is linked to dominance hierarchies for both males and females. Higher-ranking females have more offspring than lower-ranking females, and the dominant male will have the most number of offspring in the troupe. This is because the offspring of dominant females have a higher chance of survival due to better access to food and a decreased likelihood of being harassed by low-ranking females (van Noordwijk et al., 1988). Dominant males have higher reproductive success because they mate guard their females more effectively (Lang, 2006). Females have noticeable swelling in the anogenital region and produce distinct copulation calls when they are sexually ready. Generally, long-tailed macaques have two classes of vocalizations; harsh calls, used mostly for alarm, and clear calls, which promote friendly interactions.‚Ä®
6. Predation: Does the animal have any predators?
The long-tailed macaque is mostly predated on by large carnivores (e.g. tigers), large reptiles (e.g. snakes and crocodiles), and large birds of prey (e.g. eagles) (Global Invasive Species Database, 2007). ‚Ä®
7. Conservation Status
According to IUCN, the Macaca fascicularis is in the ‚ÄúLeast Concern‚Äù category, meaning that the species is not under any significant threat of extinction (Ong et al., 2008).

8.¬†Did You Know?
The long-tailed macaques, as like many other primates, are known for their creative and deft manipulation of tools. In Singapore, where this particular individual was observed, macaques have been observed to carry out ‚Äúleaf-washing‚Äù behaviours. Chiang observed long-tailed macaques performing washing behaviour to remove potentially harmful or unpleasant substances from potentially food items (Chiang, 1967). Macaques are also known to use other creative extractive foraging techniques (Pal et al., 2017) and tools (Gumert et al., 2013) based on their environments. Long-tailed macaques are highly intelligent primates!

The long-tailed macaque is the only commonly seen species of monkey in Singapore. Its population numbers some 1,500 individuals. Most dwell in and on the fringes of our rainforest nature reserves ‚Äì the Bukit Timah and the Central Catchment Nature Reserves. They also occupy parks such as Bukit Batok Nature Park, Yishun Park and Admiralty Park, as well as Sisters Islands and Pulau Ubin. We saw many of it during our visit to Pulau Ubin ‚Äî most of them being quite aggressive to humans! Holding plastic bags is a big no when walking around nature reserves as these macaques will steal them away from you!
